{{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Ely Eel Day |type = local |longtype = Cultural, Historical |image = |caption = |official_name = |nickname = Eel Festival Weekend |observedby = Inhabitants of [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]] |begins = |ends = |scheduling = first Saturday before Early May Bank Holiday |week_ordinal = |weekday = Saturday |month = |date2014 = 3 May |date2015 = 2 May |date2016 = 30 April |date2017 = 29 April |date2018 = 5 May |date2019 = 4 May |date2020 = 2 May |celebrations = parade, eel throwing competition |duration = 1 day |frequency = annual |observances = |relatedto = }}
'''Ely Eel Day''' is an annual celebration observed by people from [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]], [[Cambridgeshire]] to celebrate the city's namesake &mdash; the eel. The celebrations start with a parade which begins from Cross Green outside [[Ely Cathedral]] and proceeds through the city to the Jubilee Gardens, passing by the Market Square and along the River Great Ouse at Ely's Waterside.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ely People - Eel Day Festival 2011 |url=http://www.elypeople.co.uk/groups/local-events/Ely-rsquo-s-Eel-Festival-Big-Hit/story-11078170-detail/story.html |publisher=Elypeople.co.uk |accessdate=2014-02-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020123121/http://www.elypeople.co.uk/groups/local-events/Ely-rsquo-s-Eel-Festival-Big-Hit/story-11078170-detail/story.html |archivedate=2013-10-20 |df= }}</ref>
The celebrations following the parade include an eel throwing competition. The competition does not use real eels. Originally competitors were given socks rolled into some tights with rice in the end to weight it down<ref name='presspack'>{{cite news | first=Oscar | last=Haines | coauthors= | title=I defended my eel-throwing title!|date=2007-04-29|publisher=BBC|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_6600000/newsid_6605400/6605443.stm | work =[[Newsround|Newsround Online]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-05-01 | language = }}</ref> but now the competition uses specially made toy eels. Other events on Eel Day include an annual competition for Town Criers.<ref name="elypeople.co.uk">{{cite web|title=Ely People - Eel Day Festival 2012 Competition Results |url=http://www.elypeople.co.uk/Eel-Day-Ely-ndash-Eel-Throwing-amp-Town-Crier/story-16032450-detail/story.html |publisher=Elypeople.co.uk |accessdate=2014-02-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221223122/http://www.elypeople.co.uk/Eel-Day-Ely-ndash-Eel-Throwing-amp-Town-Crier/story-16032450-detail/story.html |archivedate=2014-02-21 |df= }}</ref>
It is traditional for any couples marrying that weekend to be named 'the King of Eels' and 'the Queen of Eels'.{{cn|date=April 2017}} Legend goes that eels bring good luck for married life.{{cn|date=April 2017}} Accordingly, the City of Ely will send couples married that weekend a hamper of eels each year on their anniversary.{{cn|date=April 2017}} As part of the Eel Parade, the Queen of Eels must march ahead of the various floats and processions on a carriage, wearing a crown of (live) eels.{{cn|date=April 2017}}
Eel Day is traditionally held on the Saturday, of the May Bank Holiday weekend.<ref name="adec">{{cite web | title = elys_annual_eel_day | url=http://www.adec.org.uk/adec/eventdetail/elys_annual_eel_day | publisher=Arts Development East Cambridgeshire | accessdate = 2011-04-30}}</ref>
